		h4.cd Summary
		p.cd I am an undergraduate researcher in the UMD MEMS and Microfluidics Lab (MML) run by Dr. Don DeVoe. Over the last year and a half, I have been pioneering a bead-based immunoassay for Ebola detection with a simple trick to improve optical clarity of an otherwise translucent matrix.
		p.cd Quick and efficient disease diagnostics require precision, innovation, and ingenuity. Current diagnostic tests are often performed by lab technicians and can take 12 to 24 hours to heed results. Accurate and reliable results can influence treatment plans and avoid unnecessary follow up appointments. I am developing a rapid, microfluidic technology that simplifies the diagnostic process. The final product is a tool that can be integrated into a sample preparation device to be used by a variety of audiences including primary care physicians and doctors in developing countries.
